#compdef memento
# ============================================================================
#  _memento — memento: development-only HTTP cache + replay tool
#             — records HTTP responses on first call, replays
#             cached responses on subsequent calls; useful for
#             FRONTEND DEVELOPMENT where you want stable mock
#             responses from real backend APIs, or for OFFLINE
#             DEMOS where the backend may be unreachable
#             (Antoine Chalifour — French developer/consultant)
#
#  Source-direct extraction from
#    https://github.com/antoinechalifour/memento/blob/master/src/cli.ts
#      (Vorpal interactive-REPL command tree)
#    https://github.com/antoinechalifour/memento/blob/master/package.json (bin: memento)
#    https://github.com/dthree/vorpal (the dthree/vorpal library
#    by David "dthree" Caccavella — also creator of dthree/cash,
#    dthree/chalk-pipe, and other Node CLI tooling)
#
#  Maintained by Antoine Chalifour (French software developer,
#  consultant).  393 GH stars.  memento is a DEVELOPMENT-ONLY
#  proxy that sits between your frontend and the backend API:
#  the FIRST request to any unique URL is forwarded to the
#  upstream backend and the RESPONSE IS RECORDED to a local
#  cache; SUBSEQUENT requests to the same URL replay the cached
#  response instantly without hitting the backend.  Useful for:
#  (a) FRONTEND DEVELOPMENT with stable mock data (no
#  flaky-backend / changing-data problems during UI work); (b)
#  OFFLINE DEMOS where the backend may be unreachable; (c) E2E
#  TESTING with deterministic API responses; (d) DEVELOPMENT
#  WITHOUT INTERNET access for parts of the stack.  After memento
#  is configured + started, the user runs `memento` in a separate
#  terminal to enter an INTERACTIVE VORPAL REPL where they can
#  inspect/clear/refresh/import the cache contents.  Sister
#  tools: mockserver (Java MockServer), smocker (Go HTTP mock —
#  IN CORPUS via _smocker R421), wiremock (Java industry-
#  standard), mountebank (Node.js — IN CORPUS via _mb),
#  mockoon (Electron GUI — IN CORPUS via _mockoon), prism-cli
#  (Stoplight OpenAPI mock — IN CORPUS via _prism), httpbin
#  (Postman's HTTP inspection — IN CORPUS via _httpbin), nock
#  (Node.js HTTP mock library), polly.js (Netflix HTTP recording).
#
#  CLI library taxonomy update: 20th TypeScript/Node CLI library
#  — David "dthree" Caccavella's **vorpal** (dthree/vorpal).
#  TypeScript-Node ecosystem now has 20 documented CLI libraries
#  — TYING WITH RUST AND GO at the top of the cross-language
#  taxonomy in a THREE-WAY TIE at 20 each.  🎉 TypeScript-Node
#  REACHES ROUND-NUMBER MILESTONE OF 20 — three-way tie restored.
#
#  vorpal (dthree/vorpal, 5,633 GH stars) is "Node's framework
#  for interactive CLIs."  Distinguishing philosophy:
#  INTERACTIVE REPL-FIRST CLI FRAMEWORK — vorpal is to commander/
#  oclif what Bash IS to single-shot scripts.  Instead of
#  building a single-shot CLI that exits after one command,
#  vorpal builds a PERSISTENT INTERACTIVE SHELL where the user
#  enters commands, the shell processes them, and the prompt
#  returns for the next command.  Use cases: REPL-style ops
#  consoles (Redis-cli-style interactive tools), interactive
#  blockchain wallets (Loom Plasma CLI, EVM-Lite CLI), interactive
#  device controllers (LIFX shell, iTunes remote, EV charger
#  control), interactive game shells (chess REPLs, MUD clients).
#  Used by antoinechalifour/memento (HTTP cache 393 stars),
#  mischah/itunes-remote (iTunes CLI 435 stars), antoinechalifour/
#  memento, loomnetwork/plasma-cli (Loom Plasma CLI 43 stars),
#  ristomatti/lifxsh (LIFX lamp shell 10 stars), mosaicnetworks/
#  evm-lite-cli (EVM-Lite CLI), DTeam-Top/cfox (CodeFox CLI),
#  energychain/evcharger (EV charger control), mosaicnetworks/
#  monetcli (Monet blockchain CLI), tineola/tineola
#  (Hyperledger Fabric tools), kfox/acclimate, mischah/itunes-
#  remote, 0xs34n/blockchain-cli (blockchain teaching),
#  shengxinjing/iblockchain (blockchain demo), serebrov/so-
#  questions (StackOverflow questions CLI).  vorpal is also the
#  basis for `dthree/cash`, dthree's own interactive Unix shell
#  alternative.
#
#  vorpal API:
#    import Vorpal from 'vorpal'
#
#    const vorpal = new Vorpal()
#
#    // SET the interactive prompt prefix
#    vorpal.delimiter('mytool$ ')
#
#    // REGISTER commands with their REPL syntax + handlers
#    vorpal
#      .command('config', 'Display current configuration')
#      .action(async function(this: Vorpal.CommandInstance) {
#        // `this.log()` writes to the REPL output
#        // `this` provides access to the current command instance
#        this.log('Config: ...')
#      })
#
#    // Commands with POSITIONAL arguments use angle brackets
#    // `<required>` and `[optional]` syntax (commander-style)
#    vorpal
#      .command('clear <requestId>', 'Clear request from cache')
#      .autocomplete({
#        data() {                            // dynamic completion
#          return getCachedRequestIds()      // returns Promise<string[]>
#        },
#      })
#      .action(async function(this: Vorpal.CommandInstance, args) {
#        await clearRequest(args.requestId)
#      })
#
#    // Commands with OPTIONS via `.option()`
#    vorpal
#      .command('info <requestId>', 'Show request info')
#      .option('-b, --body', 'Include response body')
#      .action(async function(this: Vorpal.CommandInstance, args) {
#        const includeBody = args.options.body
#      })
#
#    // SUBCOMMANDS via space-separated command strings
#    vorpal
#      .command('config reload', 'Reload configuration')
#      .action(async function() { /* ... */ })
#
#    // START the interactive REPL — blocks until user types
#    // `exit` or hits Ctrl-C
#    vorpal.show()
#
#  vorpal distinctive features:
#    - INTERACTIVE REPL via `vorpal.show()` — starts a persistent
#      prompt (configurable via `vorpal.delimiter('mytool$ ')`)
#      that reads commands from stdin, parses + dispatches them,
#      then loops back for the next input
#    - COMMAND SYNTAX: `vorpal.command('verb <required> [optional]
#      [more...]', 'description')` — commander-style positional
#      syntax with `<required>` and `[optional]` notation
#    - SPACE-SEPARATED SUBCOMMANDS — `vorpal.command('config
#      reload', '...')` registers `config reload` as a single
#      command (the space is part of the command identifier; no
#      need for separate AddCommand-style tree assembly)
#    - PER-COMMAND OPTIONS via `.option('-X, --name <value>',
#      'description')` — commander.js-style option syntax
#      attached to a command
#    - DYNAMIC AUTOCOMPLETE via `.autocomplete({ data() { return
#      Promise<string[]>... } })` — vorpal calls the data()
#      function when the user hits TAB to suggest contextual
#      completions (e.g. memento's `clear <requestId>` shows
#      currently-cached request IDs)
#    - ACTION HANDLERS — `.action(async function(this:
#      CommandInstance, args) { ... })` where `this` is the
#      command instance (provides `this.log()` for REPL output,
#      `this.prompt()` for nested questions, `this.delimiter()`
#      to change prompt mid-command)
#    - PROMPTS via `this.prompt()` — inquirer.js-style nested
#      interactive prompts within a command (e.g. confirmation
#      dialogs, multi-step wizards)
#    - HISTORY via readline integration — UP/DOWN arrow keys
#      cycle through previous commands (persistent across
#      sessions if `vorpal.historyStoragePath()` is set)
#    - CTRL-C / CTRL-D / `exit` to leave the REPL
#    - HELP via `help` and `help <command>` — auto-generated
#      from command descriptions + option descriptions
#    - DELIMITERS — `vorpal.delimiter()` sets the prompt; can be
#      changed dynamically by command handlers (e.g. switch to
#      "mytool[debug]$ " when entering debug mode)
#    - MODE-SWITCHING via `vorpal.mode()` — enter a "mode" where
#      different commands are available; useful for nested
#      shells (e.g. configuration mode in a router CLI)
#    - SINGLE-SHOT MODE via `vorpal.parse(process.argv)` — same
#      command tree can run as ONE-SHOT CLI (commands as argv)
#      instead of interactive REPL; useful for scripting
#    - INSPIRED BY Cisco IOS / Juniper Junos / network-device
#      CLIs (interactive shell with hierarchical command
#      modes); David Caccavella designed vorpal after frustration
#      with one-shot Node CLIs that couldn't preserve state
#      between commands
#  Distinct from R236 commander (TJ chained-builder — vorpal
#  borrows commander's `<arg>`/`[opt]` syntax but adds REPL on
#  top), R237 oclif (Heroku/Salesforce class-based + decorators
#  — oclif is one-shot CLI; vorpal is REPL), yargs (Bash-style),
#  R398 meow (Sindre zero-config), R399 minimist, R400 cac
#  (Anthony Fu), R403 clipanion (Yarn's class-based with
#  decorators), R406 vercel/arg, R409 mri, R412 citty (UnJS
#  declarative-schema), R415 cmd-ts (parser-combinator), R418
#  gluegun (TOOLBOX), R422 cleye, R428 @caporal/core (Mathieu
#  Robin's enterprise framework with integrated logger), R432
#  @effect/cli (Effect-TS algebraic effect system), R433
#  @stricli/core (Bloomberg LP's zero-deps), R439 vadimdemedes/
#  pastel (Next.js-for-CLI with Ink-rendered React UI).
#  TypeScript-Node documented libraries so far: commander,
#  oclif, yargs, meow, minimist, cac, clipanion, arg, mri, sade,
#  citty, cmd-ts, gluegun, cleye, @caporal/core, @effect/cli,
#  @stricli/core, pastel, vorpal (this round)... 20 total.  🎉
#  ROUND-NUMBER MILESTONE: TypeScript-Node crosses 20 documented
#  CLI libraries.  vorpal's distinguishing feature vs all other
#  TS-Node libs: vorpal is the ONLY ONE that builds INTERACTIVE
#  REPL-FIRST CLI SHELLS (persistent prompt, command history,
#  nested prompts, mode-switching) rather than one-shot CLIs.
#  Every other TS-Node lib in the corpus is designed for
#  single-shot invocation (commander/oclif/yargs/etc. all
#  parse argv once and exit).  vorpal's approach: INTERACTIVE-
#  REPL-FIRST framework with `new Vorpal().delimiter(prompt).
#  command(verb, desc).option(spec, desc).autocomplete(fn).
#  action(handler).show()` chained-builder + COMMANDER-STYLE
#  positional syntax `<required>`/`[optional]`/`[rest...]` +
#  space-separated subcommand identifiers (no AddCommand tree
#  needed) + DYNAMIC AUTOCOMPLETE via `data()` function +
#  ACTION handlers with `this: CommandInstance` providing
#  `log/prompt/delimiter` + INQUIRER-STYLE nested prompts via
#  `this.prompt()` + HISTORY + MODE-SWITCHING via `vorpal.mode
#  ()` + SINGLE-SHOT mode via `vorpal.parse(process.argv)` +
#  CTRL-C/exit to leave REPL + INSPIRED BY Cisco IOS / Juniper
#  Junos / network-device CLIs — corpus's **first documented
#  interactive-REPL-first TypeScript-Node CLI library**.  Brings
#  cross-language CLI library taxonomy variant count to 181;
#  TypeScript-Node ecosystem now has 20 documented CLI libraries
#  — TYING WITH RUST AND GO at the top of the cross-language
#  taxonomy in a THREE-WAY TIE at 20.
#
#  Surface (verbatim from `src/cli.ts` Vorpal command
#  registrations):
#
#  Usage:
#    memento [options]              # Starts the interactive
#                                   # Vorpal REPL on the
#                                   # `memento$ ` prompt
#
#  Process-level options (inherited from package.json bin
#  entrypoint setup):
#    -h, --help                     Show launcher help
#    -v, --version                  Show memento version
#
#  REPL commands (typed INSIDE the `memento$ ` prompt after
#  launching the binary; not direct shell argv):
#    config                         Display current configuration
#    config reload                  Reload the configuration file
#    ls                             List all cached requests
#    clear all                      Clear all requests from cache
#    clear <requestId>              Clear specific request from
#                                   cache (AUTOCOMPLETE — TAB
#                                   shows cached IDs)
#    refresh <requestId>            Invalidate cache for request
#                                   (next call will hit backend)
#                                   (AUTOCOMPLETE)
#    info <requestId>               Show request + response info
#                                   (AUTOCOMPLETE)
#      -b, --body                   Include the response body
#    set response-time <requestId> <ms>
#                                   Set response time for request
#                                   (requires useRealResponseTime
#                                   = true in config)
#    import                         Import curl commands from
#                                   clipboard or piped input
#    help                           Show available commands
#    help <command>                 Show help for specific command
#    exit                           Exit the REPL (Ctrl-C / Ctrl-D
#                                   also exit)
#
#  Examples:
#    memento                                    # Launch the interactive REPL
#    memento$ config                            # Show config
#    memento$ ls                                # List cached
#    memento$ clear all                         # Clear all
#    memento$ info abc123 -b                    # Info with body
#    memento$ refresh abc123                    # Refresh request
#    memento$ set response-time abc123 500      # Set delay to 500ms
#    memento$ import                            # Import curl
#    memento$ help                              # List commands
#    memento$ help info                         # Per-command help
#    memento$ exit                              # Leave REPL
#
#  Dup-skipped neighbors during hunt (in corpus or smaller user base,
#  also dthree/vorpal users):
#    - itunes-remote (mischah/itunes-remote 435 stars iTunes CLI;
#      iTunes deprecated on macOS 10.15+ in favor of Music.app;
#      FUTURE candidate if updated to Music.app)
#    - plasma-cli (loomnetwork/plasma-cli 43 stars Loom Plasma-
#      Cash blockchain CLI; FUTURE)
#    - lifxsh (ristomatti/lifxsh 10 stars LIFX lamp shell; FUTURE)
#    - evm-lite-cli (mosaicnetworks/evm-lite-cli 1 star — too
#      niche)
#    - tineola (tineola/tineola Hyperledger Fabric tools — FUTURE)
#    - cash (dthree/cash — dthree's own Unix shell alternative
#      built on vorpal; FUTURE)
#    - dthree/vorpal repo itself (5,633 stars library not CLI)
# ============================================================================

_memento() {
  local context state state_descr line
  typeset -A opt_args

  _arguments -s -S \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show launcher help]' \
    '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[show memento version]'
}

_memento "$@"
